{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to use a " }{TEXT 
263 9 "for loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task since we are do
ing a repetitive calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 29 "Note: \+
 Also, the the command " }{TEXT 265 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 15 " unfortun
ately " }{TEXT 266 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off the coefficien
ts in order." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 4 "The " }{TEXT 259 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a fo
rmula for finding the coefficients of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 
0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " 
}{TEXT 267 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious that the co
efficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^(n-k)*b^k;" "6#*&)%\"aG,&%\"nG\"\"\"
%\"kG!\"\"F()%\"bGF)F(" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 268 
1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 269 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is gi
ven by the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 270 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 
8 " of the " }{TEXT 294 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " }{TEXT 271 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 295 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in the expansi
on " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F
&F&" }{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"b
GF%" }{TEXT -1 5 " ),  " }{TEXT 272 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The
 number of combinations of " }{TEXT 273 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects c
hoosing " }{TEXT 274 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 12 " at a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 
"C(n,k);" "6#-%\"CG6$%\"nG%\"kG" }{TEXT -1 27 ", is given by the formu
la  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "C(n,k) = n!/(k!*(n-k)!);" "6#/-%\"CG6$%\"nG%\"kG
*&-%*factorialG6#F'\"\"\"*&-F+6#F(F--F+6#,&F'F-F(!\"\"F-F4" }{TEXT -1 
2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 261 10 
"State the " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 
275 31 "and use Maple to demonstrate it" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }{TEXT 297 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 "
 gives a formula for finding the coefficients of the expansion of " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "
  for any " }{TEXT 298 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious
 that the coefficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^(n-k)*b^k;" "6#*&)%\"aG,
&%\"nG\"\"\"%\"kG!\"\"F()%\"bGF)F(" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of \+
" }{TEXT 299 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 300 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 46 " is given by the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 301 1 "k
" }{TEXT -1 8 " of the " }{TEXT 304 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " 
}{TEXT 302 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 305 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in \+
the expansion " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&
F&,&F%F&F'F&F&" }{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"a
G\"\"\"%\"bGF%" }{TEXT -1 5 " ),  " }{TEXT 303 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 70 " ti
mes . I know that was cheesy but who better to define this but you." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sum(binomial(n,
k),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)binomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT 
-1 34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here the symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#
%&SigmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek letter Sigma) stands for sum.   (See t
he worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 80 "for n from 1 to 10\ndo Sum(binomial
(n,k),k=0..n) = sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n);\nod;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"\"%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"\"#" }}
