"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 206 "second line-do a series of calculations, give th
e coefficients for the equation a+1 to the nth power, and look at the \+
variable a and give the coefficient with the power i.  Look for powers
 of i from 0 to 10" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In
 this exericse we study the basic properties of polynomials and ration
al functions.  Some revelant Maple commands will be   factor, expand, \+
solve, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn is how to d
efine a function.  There are two ways, each with its own advantages an
d disadvantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a \+
" }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymbolic expression in x" }{TEXT -1 
119 " in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colon before the \+
=, this is always required when defining something.)  " }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define the sam
e polynomial as " }{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on the variable x" }
{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
